   {:e #blake3 "7e1278a9a379b5a9bdc6b63c265e0c50ff8b09eb95bb0291dec62084af14f4e0" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :task/t-6c688342; Session entity: :task/t-fc8f377d; UAQ-9 REVISION: The A/B test is now richer. Three composition variants to test: (A) Cost-aware alpha = E[delta_F(S)] / cost — the ADR-019 formulation. (B) Cost-blind product = impact * relevance * novelty * confidence — the original UAQ v1 formulation. (C) Cost-aware weighted-sum = (w1*impact + w2*relevance + w3*novelty + w4*confidence) / cost. The A/B test during external dog-food should measure which produces lowest mean prediction error and highest productive action rate. The formulation defaults to (A) — this is the theoretically correct one. But empirical validation may show that (B) is simpler and good enough, or that (C) allows factor compensation that (A) vetoes. The config datom :policy/acquisition-composition with values 'alpha', 'product', 'weighted-sum' selects the variant. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-025, INV-FOUNDATION-011.; Session entity: :recon/trace-9961039ecff10bc9; Session entity: :recon/trace-c36a7e4e29188fea; Session entity: :task/t-53f3695a; UAQ CRITICAL REVISION: COST-AWARE ACQUISITION FUNCTION. The current UAQ tasks (v2) use product composition: A = impact * relevance * novelty * confidence. The ORIGINAL ADR-FOUNDATION-019 (Session 034) specifies: alpha(action|store) = E[delta_F(S)] / cost(action). This is fundamentally better. ANALYSIS: (1) Product composition picks the highest absolute expected value. Cost-aware composition picks the highest VALUE PER UNIT COST. (2) For context blocks: cost = token count. alpha = E[delta_F(S)] / tokens. This naturally optimizes token efficiency — the Markov blanket maximizes information transfer per token. A 10-token block with 0.005 expected improvement (alpha=0.0005) outranks a 100-token block with 0.01 improvement (alpha=0.0001). (3) For tasks: cost = wall_time estimate. alpha = E[delta_F(S)] / time. This is ROI — maximize improvement per unit time. (4) For ceremony: cost = ceremony_tokens. alpha = E[improved_M(t)] / methodology_cost. (5) The product formula becomes HOW we compute E[delta_F(S)]: expected_delta_fs = impact * relevance * novelty * confidence. Then alpha = expected_delta_fs / cost. Both formulas coexist — product computes the numerator, division by cost produces the ranking. IMPACT: UAQ-1 must include ObservationCost struct and ObservationKind enum (8 kinds from ADR-019, start with 3). AcquisitionScore needs expected_delta_fs, cost, and alpha fields. Ranking by alpha not composite. ORIGINAL 8 KINDS: Task, Extraction, Review, WitnessRefresh, BoundaryCheck, CouplingExploration, CalibrationMeasurement, AnomalyInvestigation. Start with 3 (Task, Block, Boundary), rest are Phase E extensibility.; Session entity: :recon/trace-d9fee23da0eec039; Session entity: :recon/trace-d3b02b19a343c094; UAQ INSIGHT 11: BLOCK COST IS ALREADY COMPUTED. ContextBlock already has a tokens: usize field — the estimated token count. This IS the cost for context blocks. The cost-aware alpha formula alpha = expected_delta_fs / tokens is IMMEDIATELY computable with NO new infrastructure for blocks. For tasks, cost can default to a heuristic: simple tasks = 300s (5min), moderate = 1800s (30min), complex = 7200s (2hr), based on priority or estimated LOC. The ObservationCost.total_cost() method can return tokens directly for blocks and time_estimate for tasks. This means UAQ-1v2 can produce MEANINGFUL alpha values from day one — no training data needed for the cost side. The learning loop only needs to calibrate expected_delta_fs (the numerator). The denominator (cost) is known for blocks and estimable for tasks. IMPLEMENTATION SHORTCUT: In UAQ-3 (block scoring), alpha = expected_delta_fs / block.tokens.max(1). This single line change makes the ACP projection cost-aware. Blocks that carry a lot of information in few tokens rank higher than verbose blocks with marginal value.; UAQ INSIGHT 5: ATT PIPELINE SUBSUMPTION. The existing ATT-2 through ATT-7 tasks become SPECIAL CASES of the UAQ. ATT-1 (surprisal) = the novelty factor of A(t,x). ATT-2 (Hebbian) = the relevance factor boosted by explicit interest signals. ATT-3 (task relevance) = the relevance factor conditioned on active task. ATT-4 (wire ACP) = replacing sort-by-precedence with sort-by-acquisition-score. ATT-5 (Bayesian calibration) = the confidence factor trained from hypothesis outcomes. The UAQ doesn't REPLACE the ATT tasks — it SUBSUMES them. Instead of implementing each as a separate feature, implement A(t,x) once and each ATT feature becomes a new term in the composite score. This means the ATT EPIC and the UAQ EPIC are the SAME work under different framing. The UAQ framing is superior because it also captures R(t) routing, F(S) weighting, and ceremony adaptation — which the ATT framing misses. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-019 (UAQ), ADR-FOUNDATION-024 (Attention). VERIFICATION: After UAQ implementation, the ATT-2..7 tasks should be closeable as 'subsumed by UAQ' without any additional code.; Session entity: :session/s-1774281667; Session entity: :recon/trace-dc5830b407717aa1; Session entity: :task/t-3c728bc4; Session entity: :task/t-66588778; UAQ INSIGHT 6: EXTERNAL DOG-FOOD AS VALIDATION EXPERIMENT. The external dog-food becomes the experiment that validates the UAQ hypothesis: 'does a unified acquisition function converge faster than independent systems?' Protocol: (1) Initialize braid on external project with UAQ-enabled build. (2) Work 3 sessions, recording every recommendation event and its outcome. (3) Measure: (a) mean prediction error across ALL recommendation types, (b) F(S) convergence rate, (c) productive action rate (% of recommendations followed). (4) Compare to braid's own 36-session history where systems were independent. PREDICTION: UAQ should reach mean_error < 0.15 in 3 sessions (braid self-use took 35 sessions to reach 0.224 with fragmented calibration). FALSIFICATION: If mean_error is still above 0.20 after 3 sessions, the unified function isn't better than independent systems and the composition formula needs revision. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-019. This is the first empirical test of the three-primitive formalism (morphisms + reconciliation + acquisition function).; Session entity: :recon/trace-1d48ea85af389621; Session entity: :task/t-e1f23954; Session entity: :recon/trace-d21feb312fe6f42c; UAQ-TEST ENRICHMENT: COMPREHENSIVE TEST SPECIFICATION. The UAQ-TEST task needs these additional test cases: COST-AWARE RANKING TESTS: (1) Two blocks with same expected_delta_fs but different token counts — lower-cost block ranks higher. (2) High-impact high-cost task vs low-impact low-cost task — verify alpha ranking differs from raw impact ranking. (3) Zero-cost item (cost=0 should floor to cost=1 to avoid division by zero). (4) Infinite cost item should have alpha approaching 0. OBSERVATION KIND TESTS: (5) ObservationKind::Task items score using R(t) impact. (6) ObservationKind::ContextBlock items score using block relevance. (7) ObservationKind::BoundaryCheck items score using boundary weight. (8) Mixed ranking: task and block items compete in same sorted list. CALIBRATION INTEGRATION TESTS: (9) After recording 5 hypotheses for Task type and 5 for Block type, per-type confidence differs. (10) Per-type CalibrationReport shows separate error means. (11) Confidence factor from calibration actually changes alpha values. PROPERTY TESTS (proptest): (12) For random AcquisitionScores: alpha in [0, infinity) — unbounded above. (13) alpha is monotonically decreasing in cost for fixed numerator. (14) alpha is monotonically increasing in each of (impact, relevance, novelty, confidence) for fixed cost. (15) Two scores where all numerator factors dominate AND cost is lower: alpha must be strictly greater. E2E: (16) scripts/e2e_acquisition_function.sh — multi-session scenario: init, create tasks, add observations, run 5 commands, verify: (a) alpha values appear in verbose output, (b) block ordering changes across commands, (c) lower-cost blocks preferred for same expected value, (d) hypothesis predictions recorded with item_type field, (e) calibration report shows per-type breakdown. Each check prints [PASS]/[FAIL] with timing and diagnostic data (alpha, expected_delta_fs, cost, kind).; Session entity: :task/t-c6dab704; UAQ INSIGHT 13: METHODOLOGY IS INFORMATION — THE BASIN COMPETITION RESOLVED. The methodology vs pretrained-patterns battle (Basin A vs Basin B, ADR-GUIDANCE-002) has been framed as a behavioral competition. But methodology IS information presented in the context window. Basin A wins when methodology tokens have high alpha (high expected ΔF(S) per token). Basin B wins when methodology tokens have low alpha (the methodology isn't helping, so it gets dropped from the budget). This means the basin competition is SELF-RESOLVING under the acquisition function. If methodology works → its alpha is high → it survives budget pressure → agents follow it → F(S) improves → alpha increases (positive feedback). If methodology doesn't work → its alpha is low → it gets cut → agents ignore it → F(S) doesn't degrade (or degrades, which is detected by the calibration loop and feeds back as higher alpha for methodology in the next session). The ceremony_level function was a MANUAL approximation of this automatic process. It used k_eff thresholds to decide how much methodology to show. The acquisition function does the same thing but EMPIRICALLY: blocks that demonstrably improve F(S) survive; blocks that don't, get cut. No thresholds to tune. No manual classification of Full/Standard/Minimal. SPEC: ADR-GUIDANCE-002 (basin competition), ADR-FOUNDATION-025 (UAQ). FALSIFICATION: If the acquisition function consistently drops methodology blocks that would have improved F(S) if shown, the alpha computation is wrong (expected_delta_fs for methodology blocks is miscalibrated).; UAQ INSIGHT 4: CALIBRATION SPEEDUP — 5X DATA PER SESSION. Currently each system needs independent calibration data. R(t) needs task completion outcomes. ACP needs context usage feedback. F(S) needs boundary prediction errors. These are separate data streams. With unified A(t,x), every recommendation event (task shown, block presented, boundary measured) is a calibration data point for the SAME function. A session that produces 20 task events + 50 block presentations + 10 boundary measurements = 80 data points for one function vs 20/50/10 points for three separate functions. This means: (A) calibration converges in 3-5 sessions instead of 15-20. (B) External dog-food on a new project gets useful calibration within the FIRST session. (C) Cross-domain transfer via CRDT merge shares a SINGLE calibrated function, not five misaligned weight vectors. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-018 (Hypothesis Ledger), ADR-FOUNDATION-024 (Learned Attention). VERIFICATION: After 3 sessions of external use, mean prediction error for ALL types should be below 0.15 (vs current 0.224 for task-only).; UAQ INSIGHT 10: CROSS-PROJECT TRANSFER VIA CRDT MERGE. The original ADR-FOUNDATION-019 specifies: 'calibrated acquisition function weights are datoms, CRDT-mergeable via set union. First team pays learning cost; every subsequent team benefits.' THIS IS THE KILLER FEATURE. After 3 sessions on the Go CLI, the calibrated alpha weights exist as datoms in the Go CLI's braid store. Those datoms can be merged (set union) into ANY other project's store. The receiving project immediately gets: (1) Calibrated boundary weights (which alignment dimensions matter for this domain). (2) Calibrated confidence factors (how accurate predictions have been historically). (3) Block utility profiles (which context types are valuable). (4) Ceremony adaptation (what level of methodology works). This is ORGANIZATIONAL LEARNING as a mergeable artifact. It's not transfer learning in the ML sense (opaque weight matrix). It's TRANSPARENT transfer learning — every calibrated parameter is a datom with provenance, queryable, explainable, and individually challengeable. The policy manifest IS the learned model. The model IS data. C3 (schema as data) + C4 (CRDT merge) + ADR-019 (acquisition function) = transferable organizational learning. SPEC: C4, ADR-FOUNDATION-019, ADR-FOUNDATION-025. VERIFICATION: After external dog-food, merge the Go CLI store into braid's own store. Braid's alpha weights should change to incorporate the external calibration data. Mean prediction error should decrease on BOTH projects.; Session entity: :task/t-7bd86a52; UAQ INSIGHT 8: BRAID AS COMPILER — SOURCE IR / MIDDLE IR / TARGET IR. The acquisition function IS a compilation pipeline. Source IR = datom store (65K+ datoms, full knowledge state). Middle IR = ranked propositions (AcquisitionScore-annotated items — tasks, blocks, boundaries — ordered by composite score). Target IR = rendered tokens (ACP projection, budget-constrained, LLM-specific). The compilation passes are: (1) BOUNDARY PASS: evaluate F(S) boundaries → identify gaps → produce impact scores. (2) ROUTING PASS: compute R(t) for tasks → produce task-level AcquisitionScores. (3) CONTEXT PASS: score context blocks → produce block-level AcquisitionScores. (4) MERGE PASS: combine task scores and block scores into one ranked list (middle IR). (5) BUDGET PASS: select top-K items that fit in token budget (target IR). (6) RENDER PASS: format for specific output mode (human, agent, json, tsv). The MIDDLE IR is reusable: same ranked proposition list can be rendered differently for Claude (verbose prose), Codex (structured data), or a human dashboard (graphs). This is the compile-to-prompt paradigm from Session 029 (EPIC t-f5300190, closed as superseded) — but now grounded in the UAQ formalism. The middle IR IS the sorted Vec<(AcquisitionScore, Item)>. No new type needed — it's the natural output of the acquisition function applied to all items. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-025, ADR-FOUNDATION-019.; Session entity: :task/t-31557443; Session entity: :recon/trace-5ddb80258a7dc0b6; Session entity: :recon/trace-79fb13c644622701; UAQ INSIGHT 2: THE UNIVERSAL ACQUISITION FUNCTION. All five optimization systems answer the same question: 'Given current knowledge, what is the expected value of presenting/recommending/measuring X at time t?' This is the acquisition function A(t,x) from Bayesian optimization applied to epistemology. A(t,x) = E[delta-F(S) | present(x,t)] * confidence(x,t). Decomposes into: A(t,x) = impact(x) * relevance(x,task) * novelty(x,session) * confidence(x,history). Where: impact = R(t) PageRank+betweenness+critical_path, relevance = task-conditioned score, novelty = 1/sqrt(presentation_count), confidence = 1 - mean_error(boundary(x)). Each factor maps to an existing system. The acquisition function COMPOSES them instead of running them independently. This eliminates the category distinction between 'what to do' and 'what to know' — a context block IS a recommendation, a task recommendation IS context. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-019 (UAQ), ADR-FOUNDATION-015 (Observer Formalism). ALGEBRAIC PROPERTY: A(t,x) is monotonically decreasing in presentation_count (novelty decay), monotonically increasing in calibration data (confidence improvement), and task-conditioned (relevance shifts with active task). VERIFICATION: After implementation, there should be exactly ONE scoring function called for all recommendation types. Five separate ranking mechanisms collapse to one sort_by(acquisition_score).; Session entity: :recon/trace-1f17da5e7af50703; UAQ INSIGHT 1: FIVE INDEPENDENT OPTIMIZATION SYSTEMS. Braid currently has five independent systems that each decide what to recommend/show/measure, each with separate weights and calibration: (1) R(t) routing — 6-feature weighted score for task ranking, hardcoded DEFAULT_ROUTING_WEIGHTS. (2) ACP attention — static OutputPrecedence ordering for context blocks, no learning. (3) F(S) boundaries — bootstrap policy boundary weights, only HL-CALIBRATE wiring exists (not yet producing real adjustments). (4) Ceremony level — k_eff threshold mapping to Full/Standard/Minimal, no learning. (5) Harvest urgency — 4-signal max() function, no learning. These systems don't share information. R(t) doesn't know which context blocks were useful. ACP doesn't know which tasks got completed. F(S) boundaries don't know which ceremony level produced best outcomes. Each optimizes its narrow objective without seeing the whole picture. This is the open loop that subsumes all other open loops. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-019 (Universal Action Queue), ADR-FOUNDATION-024 (Learned Attention). VERIFICATION: After unification, all five decision types should be scored by one function, and calibration data from any type should improve predictions for all types.; Session entity: :recon/trace-83726983bc388d15; Session entity: :task/t-e08de1aa; Session entity: :recon/trace-c29cc7e0113d24ce; UAQ INSIGHT 12: THERE ARE NOT FIVE SYSTEMS. There is ONE system with five SOURCES of context blocks. The ceremony level isn't a 'decision about methodology enforcement.' It's a context block that says 'follow this process' competing for token budget against blocks that say 'do this task' or 'check this boundary.' The harvest warning isn't a 'decision about when to harvest.' It's a context block that says 'run braid harvest' competing against all other blocks. Every output of the system is a context block. Every context block has an expected_delta_fs and a cost (tokens). The acquisition function alpha = expected_delta_fs / tokens handles ALL of them. CONSEQUENCE: ceremony_level() and harvest_urgency_multi() don't need to be 'integrated' into the acquisition function. They need to be RECOGNIZED as already being context blocks that should be scored by the acquisition function. The separate functions exist because we didn't see that all system outputs are the same type. UAQ-7 and UAQ-8 become: ensure ceremony and harvest recommendation blocks are scored and ranked alongside task and coherence blocks. No new scoring logic — just ensure these blocks carry AcquisitionScore. The architecture simplifies because the insight removes a false distinction. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-025, INV-FOUNDATION-011.; Session entity: :recon/trace-d184a017fac136e5; Session entity: :task/t-0bee0f20; UAQ-6 ENRICHMENT: PRESENTATION TRACKING SPECIFICATION. The presentation tracking system needs precise specification: ENTITY SCHEMA: One :attention/* entity per (block-label, session) pair. Entity ident pattern: :attention/{block-label}-{session-millis}. Attributes per entity: :attention/block-label (String), :attention/presentation-count (Long, incremented per presentation), :attention/last-presented (Instant, updated per presentation), :attention/hebbian-boost (Double, set by verbose detection), :attention/learned-weight (Double, from calibration), :attention/calibration-count (Long). TRANSACTION TIMING: Batch at end of command execution, not inline during rendering. Collect presented-block-labels during project(), transact once after output is written. This avoids store modification during a read path. DOUBLE-COUNT PREVENTION: If the same block appears in both braid status and braid seed in the same command invocation, count it ONCE. Use a per-command BTreeSet of presented labels. CROSS-SESSION PERSISTENCE: At session start, load prior session's :attention/* entities. Decay hebbian_boost by 0.5 (half-life per session). Preserve learned_weight and calibration_count (cross-session learning). Reset presentation_count to 0 (session-scoped). SPEC: INV-ATTENTION-002 (presentation count semantics). FILE: crates/braid/src/main.rs (post-command tracking), crates/braid-kernel/src/context.rs (block label canonicalization).; Session entity: :recon/trace-d673a3f43ed396e8; Session entity: :recon/trace-03b4da62829a9121; DOGFOOD-4 REVISION: Transfer is reconciliation. DOGFOOD-4 reframed: not 'copy weights from Go CLI to braid' but 'merge stores and observe how reconciliation handles cross-domain hypotheses.' No boundary name matching needed. The hypothesis ledger measures prediction accuracy regardless of origin. Per-boundary errors that spike after merge indicate domain-specific calibration (not transferable). Per-boundary errors that decrease indicate the additional data helped (transferable). The merge IS an observation at the inter-project level. The quality of the merge IS data for meta-calibration.; Session entity: :recon/trace-2ba50fe1150580f4; Session entity: :task/t-fe646c79; UAQ INSIGHT 3: IMPLEMENTATION PATH — UNIFICATION NOT REWRITE. The UAQ is not a new system. It is the UNIFICATION of five existing systems into one parameterized function. Step 1: Define AcquisitionScore struct = {impact: f64, relevance: f64, novelty: f64, confidence: f64, composite: f64}. This REPLACES AttentionScore (already in budget.rs). AttentionScore had {surprisal, hebbian_boost, learned_weight, composite}. AcquisitionScore generalizes it: surprisal=novelty, hebbian_boost is absorbed into relevance, learned_weight becomes the confidence factor. Step 2: Make compute_routing in routing.rs return AcquisitionScore instead of just impact. Add relevance (task-conditioned) and novelty (presentation-count based) factors to task scoring. Step 3: Make methodology_context_blocks in context.rs return blocks with AcquisitionScore. The same function that scores tasks now scores context blocks. Step 4: Extend hypothesis ledger to record item TYPE (task, block, boundary) so calibration is per-type. Step 5: Replace five ranking mechanisms with one: sort_by(acquisition_score.composite). ESTIMATED: ~700 LOC of changes across routing.rs, context.rs, budget.rs, policy.rs. No new modules. No new commands. External interface identical. FILE: crates/braid-kernel/src/budget.rs (AcquisitionScore replaces AttentionScore), routing.rs (unified scoring), context.rs (block scoring), policy.rs (confidence from calibration).; Session entity: :task/t-362f0ca2; Session entity: :task/t-05445296; Session entity: :recon/trace-1caa247d9846d768; Session entity: :task/t-fc784b83; UAQ INSIGHT 7: ADR CRYSTALLIZATION NEEDED. The Universal Acquisition Function needs a formal ADR before implementation. ADR-FOUNDATION-025: Universal Acquisition Function — All recommendation, projection, and measurement decisions unified through A(t,x) = impact * relevance * novelty * confidence. DECISION: Replace AttentionScore with AcquisitionScore. Replace five independent ranking systems with one parameterized function. Extend hypothesis ledger to record item type for per-type calibration. ALTERNATIVES REJECTED: (1) Keep five systems, calibrate independently — rejected because calibration is 5x slower and systems can contradict each other. (2) Merge only R(t) and ACP, keep others separate — rejected because the algebraic insight is that ALL five systems answer the same question. Partial unification loses the compositional property. (3) Design a new system from scratch — rejected because every component already exists, only the composition is missing. FALSIFICATION: The ADR is violated if any recommendation decision requires information not available in the four factors (impact, relevance, novelty, confidence). If such a case exists, a fifth factor is needed. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-019 references the UAQ concept. ADR-FOUNDATION-025 formalizes it.; Session entity: :recon/trace-7313ac220cc1c82a; UAQ INSIGHT 14: TRANSFER IS RECONCILIATION, NOT WEIGHT COPYING. Cross-project merge is not ML transfer learning (opaque weight matrix → target domain). It is reconciliation of two knowledge bases through set union (C4), the same operation used for multi-agent coordination. When store A (braid, 36 sessions) merges with store B (Go CLI, 3 sessions): schema union is automatic (same binary, same layers). Policy weights resolve via LWW (A's calibrated weights win on recency). Hypothesis merge adds A's 36 data points to B's 9 — combined dataset of 45. The calibration function computes error over ALL 45. KEY INSIGHT: The system doesn't need boundary names to match. It needs to OBSERVE that predictions fail and adjust. When A's calibrated weights produce bad predictions on B's data, that's an axiological divergence (SEED.md §6 type 6). The reconciliation taxonomy detects and classifies it. The calibration loop adjusts. The merge of two stores IS an observation. The quality of the merge (did predictions improve?) IS data for meta-calibration. THE RECURSION: Merge is harvest at the inter-project level. Harvest takes agent experience → store datoms. Merge takes another store → datoms. Both are set union. Both produce potential conflicts. Both feed through reconciliation. It's the same operation at different scales — individual observation, session harvest, cross-project merge. SPEC: C4 (CRDT merge), ADR-FOUNDATION-019 (UAQ), ADR-FOUNDATION-014 (convergence thesis). VERIFICATION: After merge, per-boundary error should be measurably different (not necessarily lower — the merge might increase error for some boundaries while decreasing for others, indicating domain-specific calibration needs).; Session entity: :recon/trace-3639d47e4bca699b; Session entity: :task/t-655e3cf2; Session entity: :recon/trace-a05ce517cfa8b347; Session entity: :recon/trace-ae5f7a621ac85628; Session entity: :recon/trace-16e4c97ee51c1e1b; Session entity: :task/t-bf3df52e; Session entity: :recon/trace-3f8cec9f940ddf17; UAQ INSIGHT 9: THREE LEARNING LOOP TIMESCALES. The UAQ operates at three timescales that must be explicitly tracked: FAST LOOP (per-session, calibration): presentation counts, follow-through rates, prediction errors. This is UAQ-4/5/6. Data: 20-80 events per session. Convergence: 3-5 sessions. Mechanism: hypothesis ledger records predictions, outcomes compute error, confidence factor adjusts. MEDIUM LOOP (per-phase, structure): boundary weight adjustment. This is HL-CALIBRATE. Data: F(S) trajectory across sessions. Convergence: 10-20 sessions. Mechanism: per-boundary mean error informs weight increase/decrease. The acquisition function's impact factor reflects updated boundary weights. SLOW LOOP (per-domain, ontology): discovering new block types or deprecating useless ones. NOT YET IMPLEMENTED. Data: block utility patterns across 50+ sessions. Convergence: unknown. Mechanism: when a new kind of information consistently scores high in the acquisition function, it should be promoted to a first-class block type. When an existing block type consistently scores zero, it should be deprecated. This is the ontological loop — the system learns not just WEIGHTS but CATEGORIES. SPEC: ADR-FOUNDATION-014 (convergence thesis), ADR-FOUNDATION-025. The slow loop is Phase E work. The fast and medium loops are Phase D (current). The UAQ architecture must SUPPORT all three loops even if only the fast loop is fully implemented now — the data structures must not preclude the medium and slow loops.\nSession entity: :task/t-24d77add; Acquisition Ranking by Alpha — items ranked by E[delta_F(S)] / cost, not by raw expected value; Session entity: :task/t-44afae2f; Session entity: :task/t-16abc78c; Session entity: :task/t-15861543; Acquisition Function Composition — A(t,x) is the unique scoring function for all recommendation types; Session entity: :task/t-f911f269; Session entity: :task/t-969ee3e8; Session entity: :task/t-f63665e2; Universal Acquisition Function — unify all recommendation decisions through A(t,x); Session entity: :task/t-f86bcab5; Session entity: :task/t-7b147c9c; All System Outputs Are Context Blocks — methodology IS information, not a separate enforcement mechanism" :op :assert}
